<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05162h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05162h">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05162h"> 162(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> teetotaller (T)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Can these Nazarites have been the Nazarenes referred to in the Jeshu story? Such a confusion of names is more than possible, for the author of our first Gospel has actually perpetrated it. He sends Jesus home to Nazareth to fulfill the prophecy &ldquo;He shall be called a Nazarene.&rdquo; But the only prophecy of that kind in the Old Testament is in the angel&apos;s diction of the birth of Samson, who was neither to shave nor to drink strong drink, but to be &ldquo;a Nazarite. from the womb.&rdquo; The Nazarite was an ancient <mark>teetotaller</mark>, and had no connexion whatever with Nazareth. <small> G.W. Foote and J.M. Wheeler, eds., <a name="SEPH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SEPH"><cite title="source">The Jewish Life of Christ</cite></a>, (1879) 46f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02110c" href="c02all.htm#c02110c">VI.C.02:110(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
